"Brewery slides just hit different, y'know?" Says 6 year old Paxton, one of many children impacted by the closing of the 'Little Explorers' corner at Old Yale Brewing. "You put in a long day of playing at home with mom and it's just great to have a nice crisp slide at the end of the day, Amongst many activities... I like to partake in a few. We always play responsibly though".

"It's tough to find nice, honest places to play these days" 4 year old Luna says, who's been a regular slider since April. "It would be really encouraging to see a shift in regulations, especially in this economy, so much of it is outdated".

"Just gotta take it one day at a time, that's all you really can do." An emotional Morghan says. The mother of Paxton and Luna. 

"It's not business, it's personal" commented the BC Liquor Branch

"There was a kids corner?" - Dax, 58, a regular at the bar
I don't think Gandalf meant for us to hike this way. Or at all.
The destroyer of the dance floor
Time to slide into those Vessis
The day the world stood still.

In light of recent events, local UAPs in the Lower Mainland area have finally broken their silence and have decided to participate in this year's Abbotsford Airshow.

"We've been wanting to get involved in the community for some time now. What better way to do that than to show what we do best? We are ecstatic to be sharing the skies with the Snowbirds this year." Says Æçß$‽‡, who is the ring leader of the recently founded Abbotsford UAP association.

His wife, №₹æ∆∞, also shared her excitement for the show this year "We could not be more thrilled, there's been a stigma about us for years now and we are eager to show that we are more than just an aerial phenomenon. It's an opportunity to give back." 

Their son, Kyle, is also looking forward to facilitating group activities on the tarmac. Which will include crop circling building & maintenance, UAP tours, and a short slideshow of their history. "It's all really important stuff, we're not in it for the money. We just want the city to be educated on us and maybe get a little taste of what our life is like. We're hoping to contract with local farmers who would be open to us using their crops to settle on. This city really does have the best crops in BC."

The UAPs have requested no photography as they are still used to hiding from cameras, however they are happy to chat about the economy over some craft beer.
Low hanging fruits of the spirit
Live, Laugh, Love a good deal

We're officially in our first week of 2024 and the semi-truck/overpass relationship continues, and it's as complicated as ever.

"I was really hoping to go the whole month without a hit. Or at least the week." The truck driver explains, as it was his New Year's resolution to have a clean month. "Carrying an oversized load just hits different. Literally." 

This marks the second overpass collision in less than a week. The hit wasn't severe and the No. 3 Rd overpass has little to no damage, to which the truck driver remarked "we'll get 'em next time."
"oh this is nothing" - annoying friend from Alberta
